---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="About - 1RM Calculator">
	<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-8">
		<!-- Page Header -->
		<div class="text-center mb-12">
			<h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold bg-gradient-to-r from-purple-400 via-pink-400 to-purple-400 bg-clip-text text-transparent mb-4">
				About 1RM Calculator
			</h1>
			<p class="text-slate-300 text-lg max-w-2xl mx-auto">
				The science behind our 1RM calculator and why accurate strength measurement matters
			</p>
		</div>

		<!-- Mission -->
		<div class="bg-slate-800/50 backdrop-blur-sm rounded-2xl p-8 mb-8 border border-slate-700/50">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-300 mb-6">üéØ Our Mission</h2>
				<p class="text-slate-300 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
					1RM Calculator was created to provide athletes, powerlifters, and fitness enthusiasts with the most accurate and user-friendly 1RM calculator available. We believe that understanding your true strength capabilities is essential for effective training programming and safe progression.
				</p>
			<p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
				Our calculator combines multiple scientifically-validated formulas to give you the most comprehensive view of your one-rep max, helping you train smarter and achieve your strength goals safely.
			</p>
		</div>

		<!-- The Science -->
		<div class="bg-slate-800/50 backdrop-blur-sm rounded-2xl p-8 mb-8 border border-slate-700/50">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-300 mb-6">üî¨ The Science Behind 1RM Calculations</h2>
			
			<div class="space-y-6">
				<div>
					<h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-white mb-3">What is a 1RM?</h3>
					<p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
						Your One-Rep Max (1RM) is the maximum amount of weight you can lift for exactly one repetition with proper form. It's the gold standard for measuring absolute strength and is crucial for designing effective training programs.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-white mb-3">Why Use Calculations?</h3>
					<p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-3">
						Testing your true 1RM frequently can be:
					</p>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-300 ml-6">
						<li>‚Ä¢ Physically demanding and potentially risky</li>
						<li>‚Ä¢ Time-consuming and requires specific preparation</li>
						<li>‚Ä¢ Not practical for regular training monitoring</li>
						<li>‚Ä¢ Difficult to perform without proper spotting</li>
					</ul>
				</div>

				<div>
					<h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-white mb-3">Research Foundation</h3>
					<p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
						Our formulas are based on decades of strength training research and have been validated across thousands of athletes. Each formula was developed by analyzing the relationship between submaximal loads and maximum strength capacity.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- Formula Details -->
		<div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
			<div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/30 rounded-2xl p-6 border border-purple-500/30">
				<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-purple-300 mb-4">üìà Epley Formula (1985)</h3>
				<p class="text-slate-300 text-sm leading-relaxed">
					Developed by Boyd Epley at the University of Nebraska. Most widely used formula in strength training. Provides reliable estimates for 2-10 rep ranges and is the standard in most strength programs.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-pink-900/30 to-pink-800/30 rounded-2xl p-6 border border-pink-500/30">
				<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-pink-300 mb-4">üìä Brzycki Formula (1993)</h3>
				<p class="text-slate-300 text-sm leading-relaxed">
					Created by Matt Brzycki, this formula tends to be more conservative and works well for higher rep ranges (6-12). Often preferred for general fitness applications.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/30 to-blue-800/30 rounded-2xl p-6 border border-blue-500/30">
				<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">‚ö° Lombardi Formula (1989)</h3>
				<p class="text-slate-300 text-sm leading-relaxed">
					Based on an exponential relationship between reps and load. Developed through extensive analysis of strength data and works well for experienced lifters.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/30 to-green-800/30 rounded-2xl p-6 border border-green-500/30">
				<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-300 mb-4">üéØ O'Conner Formula (1989)</h3>
				<p class="text-slate-300 text-sm leading-relaxed">
					A more conservative approach that often provides lower estimates. Particularly useful for beginners or when emphasizing safety over maximum performance.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- Accuracy & Limitations -->
		<div class="bg-slate-800/50 backdrop-blur-sm rounded-2xl p-8 mb-8 border border-slate-700/50">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-300 mb-6">‚öñÔ∏è Accuracy & Limitations</h2>
			
			<div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
				<div>
					<h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-white mb-4">‚úÖ Most Accurate For:</h3>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-300">
						<li>‚Ä¢ 1-6 repetition ranges</li>
						<li>‚Ä¢ Experienced lifters with good form</li>
						<li>‚Ä¢ Compound movements (squat, bench, deadlift)</li>
						<li>‚Ä¢ Well-rested, properly warmed-up lifts</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				
				<div>
					<h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-white mb-4">‚ö†Ô∏è Less Accurate For:</h3>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-300">
						<li>‚Ä¢ Very high rep ranges (15+)</li>
						<li>‚Ä¢ Isolation exercises</li>
						<li>‚Ä¢ Beginners with inconsistent form</li>
						<li>‚Ä¢ Fatigued or undertrained states</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="mt-6 p-4 bg-yellow-900/20 border border-yellow-500/30 rounded-lg">
				<p class="text-yellow-200 text-sm">
					<strong>Important:</strong> All 1RM calculations are estimates. Individual factors like training experience, muscle fiber type, and neuromuscular efficiency can affect accuracy. Always start conservatively when using calculated values in training.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- Why Choose 1RM Calculator -->
		<div class="bg-slate-800/50 backdrop-blur-sm rounded-2xl p-8 mb-8 border border-slate-700/50">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-300 mb-6">üí™ Why Choose 1RM Calculator?</h2>
			
			<div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
				<div class="text-center">
					<div class="w-16 h-16 bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-600 to-pink-600 rounded-2xl flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
						<svg class="w-8 h-8 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path>
						</svg>
					</div>
					<h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-2">Multiple Formulas</h3>
					<p class="text-slate-300 text-sm">Compare results from 4 different scientific formulas for the most comprehensive analysis.</p>
				</div>

				<div class="text-center">
					<div class="w-16 h-16 bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-600 to-pink-600 rounded-2xl flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
						<svg class="w-8 h-8 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 10V3L4 14h7v7l9-11h-7z"></path>
						</svg>
					</div>
					<h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-2">Instant Results</h3>
					<p class="text-slate-300 text-sm">Real-time calculations with training percentages and rep range recommendations.</p>
				</div>

				<div class="text-center">
					<div class="w-16 h-16 bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-600 to-pink-600 rounded-2xl flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
						<svg class="w-8 h-8 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 18h.01M8 21h8a2 2 0 002-2V5a2 2 0 00-2-2H8a2 2 0 00-2 2v14a2 2 0 002 2z"></path>
						</svg>
					</div>
					<h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-2">Mobile Friendly</h3>
					<p class="text-slate-300 text-sm">Beautiful, responsive design that works perfectly on any device, anywhere.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- Team -->
		<div class="bg-slate-800/50 backdrop-blur-sm rounded-2xl p-8 mb-8 border border-slate-700/50">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-300 mb-6">üë• Built for the Community</h2>
			<p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
				1RM Calculator is developed by strength training enthusiasts who understand the importance of accurate programming. We're committed to providing free, reliable tools that help athletes at every level achieve their goals safely and effectively.
			</p>
			<p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
				Whether you're a powerlifter preparing for competition, a CrossFit athlete working on strength gains, or a fitness enthusiast tracking progress, 1RM Calculator provides the precision and reliability you need.
			</p>
		</div>

		<!-- Call to Action -->
		<div class="text-center">
			<a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-gradient-to-r from-purple-600 to-pink-600 hover:from-purple-700 hover:to-pink-700 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg transition-all duration-200 transform hover:scale-105 shadow-lg mr-4">
				Try the Calculator
				<svg class="w-5 h-5 ml-2" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
					<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 7l5 5m0 0l-5 5m5-5H6"></path>
				</svg>
			</a>
			<a href="/guide" class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-slate-700 hover:bg-slate-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg transition-all duration-200">
				Read the Guide
			</a>
		</div>
	</div>
</Layout>
